<div class="markdown"><h2>Overview</h2>
<ol>
<li><p>Validate methods using simulated data</p>
</li>
<li><p>Validate computation</p>
</li>
<li><p>Compare Likelihood to expected distribution</p>
</li>
<li><p>Sensitivity to individual data points</p>
</li>
<li><p>Sensitivity to assumptions &#40;e.g., prior distributions&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p>Predictive distribution</p>
</li>
<li><p>Cross validation</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Validate methods using simulated data</h1>
<ul>
<li><p>Generate simulated data sets that satisfy all model assumptions.  </p>
</li>
<li><p>Apply model and computational methods to simulated data</p>
</li>
<li><p>Compare results to true parameter values.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2>Checks to perform based on simulated data:</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Are estimated model parameters close to true values?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Do estimated parameter uncertainties accurately characterize the dispersion from the true values?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Is the distribution of parameter estimates centered on their true values?</p>
</li>
<li><p>How many iterations are required for algorithms to converge?  </p>
</li>
<li><p>What can we learn reliably?    </p>
</li>
<li><p>Are there regions of parameter space that result in low quality inference?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h4>Validating methods on simulated data is a key step <br> &#40;too often overlooked&#41;</h4>
<p>This approach is very useful for diagnosing many of the most common problems:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Not enough data</p>
</li>
<li><p>Measurement uncertainties too large</p>
</li>
<li><p>Spatial or temporal sampling leads to degeneracies</p>
</li>
<li><p>Model has too many unknown parameters</p>
</li>
<li><p>Iterative algorithms don&#39;t converge reliably</p>
</li>
<li><p>Iterative algorithms take longer than expected to converge</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Real data is &#40;almost always&#41; more complicated than our idealizd model, but...  </p>
<ul>
<li><p>If our method doesn&#39;t work reliabily for idealized data, then we shouldn&#39;t trust them applied to real data.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If our method requires <span class="tex">$10^6$</span> iterations to converge for idealized data, then we know we&#39;ll need to run it for at least that long for real data &#40;and potentially longer&#41;.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Validate the computation</h1>
<p>&#40;This step applies regardless of whether analyzing simulated or real data.&#41;</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Are the results pausible?</p>
<ul>
<li><p>E.g., Magnitude of best-fit value for each model parameter</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>For algorithms that have stochastic element, are results robust to:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Different &#40;reasonable&#41; initial guesses?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Different draws from psuedo-random number generator?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>For itterative algorithms:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Why did algorithm stop?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Any warning signs of non-convergence?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>For algorithms that return an uncertainty estimate, is the reported precission:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Robust?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Scientifically useful?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Compare Likelihood to expected distribution</h1>
<p>Likelihood: </p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;eqnarray&#125;
\mathcal&#123;L&#125; &amp; &#61; &amp; p&#40; \mathrm&#123;data&#125; \; | \; \mathrm&#123;model\; parameters&#125;, \; \mathrm&#123;model&#125; &#41; \\
&amp; &#61; &amp; p &#40;y|θ,M&#41; &#61; p&#40;y|\theta&#41;
\end&#123;eqnarray&#125;$$</p>
<p>Often, we have a complex <em>physical model</em>, but a relatively simple model of the <em>measurement process</em>.  In these cases, if we knew the full model was correct and the model parameters &#40;<span class="tex">$\theta$</span>&#41;, then we can compute the distribution of the likelihood. </p>
<p>For simple measurement models, this can often be done analytically.  E.g., </p>
<ul>
<li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution">Poisson distribution</a> for sum of counts &#40;if counts are from a Poisson process&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution">χ² distribution</a> for sum of squared residuals &#40;if measurement errors are Gaussian&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-distribution"><em>F</em>-distribution</a> for ratio of two variables drawn from χ² distribution</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>For more complex measurement models, this is often done via simulation.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Sensitivity to individual data points</h1>
<p>In practice, there are usually complications omitted from the model being used for inference. </p>
<ul>
<li><p>Could be missing astrophysics &#40;e.g., sample of targets is contaminated with a small fraction of objects that different from intended sample&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p>Could be incomplete model for measurement process &#40;e.g., cosmic ray, observer points telescope at wrong object, ...&#41;</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>To procted against making poor decissions/scientific inferences:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Ask would our decisions/inferences change if a small fraction of measurements had be omitted from analysis?  </p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Sensitivity to prior distribution/assumptions</h1>
<ul>
<li><p>In a Bayesian analysis, we specify prior assumptions quantitatively by specifying a prior distribution for unknown model parameters.</p>
</li>
<li><p>There are assumptions in any model &#40;even if they&#39;re hard to find, e.g., in a frequentist test&#41;. </p>
</li>
<li><p>Usually, reasonable scientists could make different reasonable assumptions.  </p>
</li>
<li><p>The precise quantiative results will differ depending on the assumptions.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The differences in the results under different assumptions might be:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>So small they are scientifically unininteresting,</p>
</li>
<li><p>So large that more detailed analysis isn&#39;t a good use of your time,</p>
</li>
<li><p>Somewhere in the middle.  </p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>We need to know where this analysis falls along that spectrum <em>before</em> we start drawing scientific conclusions.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Predictive distribution</h1>
<ul>
<li><p>Does model make good &quot;predictions&quot; for the observed data?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>θ_true = [a_0, order_true &gt;= 1 ? a_1 : 0.0 , order_true &gt;= 2 ? a_2 : 0.0 , order_true &gt;=3 ? a_3 : 0.0];	</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    redraw_for_plot 
    x_obs, y_obs, design_matrix, _ = generate_data(θ_true[1:(order_true+1)], n_obs, σ_obs,n_outliers=n_outliers)
    plt = scatter(x_obs, y_obs, yerr=fill(σ_obs,n_obs), xlabel=L"x", ylabel=L"y_{obs}", label=:none, legend=:topleft)
    θ_fit = calc_mle_linear_model(design_matrix,y_obs, diagm(fill(σ_obs,n_obs)))
    y_pred = predict_linear_model(design_matrix,θ_fit)
    loss = round(sum(((y_obs.-y_pred)./σ_obs).^2),sigdigits=3)
    plot!(plt, x_obs,y_pred, lineweight=4, label="Full model (χ²=$loss)")
    ylim = ylims(plt)
    if order_true &gt; 1
        design_matrix_linear = view(design_matrix,:,1:2)
        θ_fit_linear = calc_mle_linear_model(design_matrix_linear,y_obs, diagm(fill(σ_obs,n_obs)))
        y_pred_linear = predict_linear_model(design_matrix_linear,θ_fit_linear)
        loss_linear = round(sum(((y_obs.-y_pred_linear)./σ_obs).^2),sigdigits=3)
        plot!(plt, x_obs,y_pred_linear, lineweight=4, label="Linear model  (χ²=$loss_linear)")
    end
    plt
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h1>Cross validation</h1>
<ul>
<li><p>Previously, we fit a model based on all of our observations and then asked if the resulting model made good &quot;predictions&quot;.  This is a relatively weak test.  </p>
</li>
<li><p>A stronger test would be to see if the model can make good predictions for new data.  </p>
</li>
<li><p>Often, acquiring new data is very time consuming.</p>
</li>
<li><p>This motivates a more powerful test, <strong>cross validation</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2>Cross validation of a single model</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Divide data into two subsets &#40;e.g., 75&#37; &quot;training&quot;, 25&#37; &quot;validation&quot;&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p>Fit data &#40;&quot;train model&quot;&#41; using only training set</p>
</li>
<li><p>Use resulting parameters to make predictions for validation set</p>
</li>
<li><p>How well did the model do?  &#40;evaluate &quot;loss function&quot;&#41;</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2>Cross validation when considering multiple models</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Divide data into <strong>three</strong> subsets &#40;e.g., 60&#37; &quot;training&quot;, 20&#37; &quot;validation&quot;, 20&#37; &quot;test&quot;&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p>For each model you want to consider:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Fit/Train using only data from training set</p>
</li>
<li><p>Validate using only data from validation set</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Pick which model you&#39;ll use for decissions/publication:</p>
</li>
<li><p>Evaluate predictions for test data set.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Report results on test data.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Avoid temptation</strong> to make further &quot;improvements&quot; at the point.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

<script>const getParentCell = el => el.closest("pluto-cell")

const getHeaders = () => {
	const depth = Math.max(1, Math.min(6, 3)) // should be in range 1:6
	const range = Array.from({length: depth}, (x, i) => i+1) // [1, ..., depth]
	
	const selector = range.map(i => `pluto-notebook pluto-cell h${i}`).join(",")
	return Array.from(document.querySelectorAll(selector))
}

const indent = true
const aside = true

const clickHandler = (event) => {
	const path = (event.path || event.composedPath())
	const toc = path.find(elem => elem?.classList?.contains?.("toc-toggle"))
	if (toc) {
		event.stopImmediatePropagation()
		toc.closest(".plutoui-toc").classList.toggle("hide")
	}
}

document.addEventListener("click", clickHandler)


const render = (el) => html`${el.map(h => {
	const parent_cell = getParentCell(h)

	const a = html`<a 
		class="${h.nodeName}" 
		href="#${parent_cell.id}"
	>${h.innerText}</a>`
	/* a.onmouseover=()=>{
		parent_cell.firstElementChild.classList.add(
			'highlight-pluto-cell-shoulder'
		)
	}
	a.onmouseout=() => {
		parent_cell.firstElementChild.classList.remove(
			'highlight-pluto-cell-shoulder'
		)
	} */
	a.onclick=(e) => {
		e.preventDefault();
		h.scrollIntoView({
			behavior: 'smooth', 
			block: 'start'
		})
	}

	return html`<div class="toc-row">${a}</div>`
})}`

const tocNode = html`<nav class="plutoui-toc">
	<header>
     <span class="toc-toggle open-toc">📖</span>
     <span class="toc-toggle closed-toc">📕</span>
	Table of Contents</header>
	<section></section>
</nav>`

tocNode.classList.toggle("aside", aside)
tocNode.classList.toggle("indent", indent)

const updateCallback = () => {
	tocNode.querySelector("section").replaceWith(
		html`<section>${render(getHeaders())}</section>`
	)
}
updateCallback()
setTimeout(updateCallback, 100)
setTimeout(updateCallback, 1000)
setTimeout(updateCallback, 5000)

const notebook = document.querySelector("pluto-notebook")


// We have a mutationobserver for each cell:
const observers = {
	current: [],
}

const createCellObservers = () => {
	observers.current.forEach((o) => o.disconnect())
	observers.current = Array.from(notebook.querySelectorAll("pluto-cell")).map(el => {
		const o = new MutationObserver(updateCallback)
		o.observe(el, {attributeFilter: ["class"]})
		return o
	})
}
createCellObservers()

// And one for the notebook's child list, which updates our cell observers:
const notebookObserver = new MutationObserver(() => {
	updateCallback()
	createCellObservers()
})
notebookObserver.observe(notebook, {childList: true})

// And finally, an observer for the document.body classList, to make sure that the toc also works when if is loaded during notebook initialization
const bodyClassObserver = new MutationObserver(updateCallback)
bodyClassObserver.observe(document.body, {attributeFilter: ["class"]})

// Hide/show the ToC when the screen gets small
let m = matchMedia("(max-width: 1000px)")
let match_listener = () => 
	tocNode.classList.toggle("hide", m.matches)
match_listener()
m.addListener(match_listener)

invalidation.then(() => {
	notebookObserver.disconnect()
	bodyClassObserver.disconnect()
	observers.current.forEach((o) => o.disconnect())
	document.removeEventListener("click", clickHandler)
	m.removeListener(match_listener)
})

return tocNode

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function generate_data(θ::AbstractVector, n::Integer, σ::Real; n_outliers::Integer = 0, outlier_factor::Real=5)
    order = length(θ)-1
    @assert 1&lt;= order &lt;= 3  # linear, quadratic or cubic model
    x = sort(rand(n))
    A = mapreduce(i-&gt;x.^i,hcat,0:order) # design matrix
    y_true = A * θ
    σ_true = fill(σ,n)
    if n_outliers&gt;=1
        idx_outliers = rand(1:n,n_outliers)
        σ_true[idx_outliers] .*= outlier_factor
    else 
        idx_outliers = Int64[]
    end
    y_obs = y_true .+ σ_true .* randn(n)
    return (;x_obs = x, y_obs, design_matrix=A, y_true, σ_true, idx_outliers)
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-generate_data' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>generate_data (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>"""
`predict_linear_model(A, b)`
Computes the predictions of a linear model with design matrix `A` and parameters `b`.
"""
function predict_linear_model(A::AbstractMatrix, b::AbstractVector)
    @assert size(A,2) == length(b)
    A*b
end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>"""
`calc_mle_linear_model(A, y_obs, covar)`
Computes the maximum likelihood estimator for b for the linear model
`y = A b`
where measurements errors of `y_obs` are normally distributed and have covariance `covar`.
"""
function calc_mle_linear_model(A::AbstractMatrix, y_obs::AbstractVector, covar::AbstractMatrix)
    @assert size(A,1) == length(y_obs) == size(covar,1) == size(covar,2)
    @assert size(A,2) &gt;= 1
    (A' * (covar \ A)) \ (A' * (covar \ y_obs) )
end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function generate_θ_fit_distribution(θ::AbstractVector, n_obs::Integer, σ::Real; n_sim::Integer = 100, order_fit::Integer = length(θ)-1, n_outliers::Integer=0) 
    output = zeros(order_fit+1, n_sim)
    for i in 1:n_sim
        x_obs, y_obs, design_matrix, _ = generate_data(θ_true, n_obs, σ, n_outliers=n_outliers)
        if length(θ) == order_fit-1  # Fit with same order as generated data
            design_matrix_fit = design_matrix
        else
            design_matrix_fit = view(design_matrix,:,1:(order_fit+1))
        end
        θ_fit = calc_mle_linear_model(design_matrix_fit,y_obs, diagm(fill(σ,n_obs)))
        output[:,i] .= θ_fit
    end
    return output
end</code></pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function plot_parameter_histograms(results::AbstractMatrix, θ_true; title::String = "")
  n_param = size(results,1)
  @assert length(θ_true) &gt;= n_param
  n_sims = size(results,2)
  n_bins = min(100,max(20,floor(Int64,n_sims//10)))
  plts = Array{eltype(plot())}(undef, n_param)
  for i in 1:n_param
    # Plot histogram of MLE estimates 
  	plts[i] = plot(xlabel=latexstring("\\theta_{$i}"), legend=:none)
    histogram!(plts[i],results[i,:],nbins=n_bins)
    # Add vertical line for true value
    ylim = ylims(plts[i])
    plot!(plts[i],fill(θ_true[i],2), [first(0), last(ylim)], linecolor=:red, lineweight=8, linestyle=:solid )
    # Annotate with standard deviation of MLEs
    xlim = xlims(plts[i])
    ann_x = xlim[1] + (xlim[2]-xlim[1])*0.95
    ann_y = ylim[1] + (ylim[2]-ylim[1])*0.8
    ann = latexstring("\\sigma_{\\theta_$i} = $(round(std(results[i,:]),sigdigits=2))")
  	annotate!(plts[i], ann_x, ann_y, text(ann,halign=:right))
  end
  if length(title) &gt;0 
      title!(plts[1],title)
  end
  plot(plts..., layout=(n_param,1))
end</code></pre>
